e:12pt">is at the v</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ery heart of an inspecto</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">r’s judgements. I</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">t is now harder for schools to be judged good or outstanding where the achievement of disadvantaged pupils is below that of other pupils. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The extent of white working class pupils’ educational underachievement</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.18pt; padding-left:2.82pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Successive reports published by Ofsted over the last twenty years have shown that there are too few good and outstanding schools serving disadvantaged pupils</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> and in areas of high or indeed average deprivation</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The performance of pupils from low income bac</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">kgrounds, especially White British families, is well below average and the gap between their attainment and that of others of the same age is too wide.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.18pt; padding-left:2.82pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">For too many </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">of these </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">disadvantaged children failure starts early. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Overall, inspection evidence shows t</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">hat Early Years provision is better than it was three years ago. However, the overall quality of provision is</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">weakest in areas of high deprivation. This is particularly the case for childminders, where the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">gap between the quality of provision in areas of h</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">igh and low deprivation is wider than for other childcare providers. This issue was discussed in detail in Ofsted’s Annual Report 2011/12.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.18pt; padding-left:2.82pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The difference in impact between attending</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">a high quality pre-school and attending a low</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">quality pre-school is grea</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ter for children who</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">come from m</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ore disadvantaged backgrounds. However, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">children from low income families are less likely</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">to attend high quality early education and care</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">programmes than their peers.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:FoundryFormSans-Book; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:FoundryFormSans-Book; font-size:12pt">The quality of schools in England has </span><span style="font-family:FoundryFormSans-Book; font-size:12pt">also </span><span style="font-family:FoundryFormSans-Book; font-size:12pt">improved</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:FoundryFormSans-Book; font-size:12pt">ove</span><span style="font-family:FoundryFormSans-Book; font-size:12pt">r time.</span><span style="font-family:FoundryFormSans-Book; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:FoundryFormSans-Book; font-size:12pt">However, i</span><span style="font-family:FoundryFormSans-Book; font-size:12pt">nspection evidence demonstrates that</span><span style="font-family:FoundryFormSans-Book; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:FoundryFormSans-Book; font-size:12pt">there are c</span><span style="font-family:FoundryFormSans-Book; font-size:12pt">lear differences in the </span><span style="font-family:FoundryFormSans-Book; font-size:12pt">quality</span><span style="font-family:FoundryFormSans-Book; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:FoundryFormSans-Book; font-size:12pt">of provision between schools serving</span><span style="font-family:FoundryFormSans-Book; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:FoundryFormSans-Book; font-size:12pt">the least and most deprived communities</span><span style="font-family:FoundryFormSans-Book; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:FoundryFormSans-Book; font-size:12pt">The proportion of good or</span><span style="font-family:FoundryFormSans-Book; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:FoundryFormSans-Book; font-size:12pt">outstanding schools in the most deprived areas</span><span style="font-family:FoundryFormSans-Book; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:FoundryFormSans-Book; font-size:12pt">is 20 </span><span style="font-family:FoundryFormSans-Book; font-size:12pt">percentage points lower than in the least</span><span style="font-family:FoundryFormSans-Book; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:FoundryFormSans-Book; font-size:12pt">deprived areas. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:FoundryFormSans-Book; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.18pt; padding-left:2.82pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Ofsted’s recent report </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Unseen Children</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> identified schools in areas of high deprivation that were bucking the trend and enabling disadvantaged pupils to achieve as well as their contemporaries</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. Ho</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">wever, the large majority of these schools were in London and a few other major cities. Typically, these schools have large concentrations of pupils from a wide range of ethnic backgrounds. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The number of successful schools with high proportions of pupils f</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">rom White British backgrounds, where the most disadvantaged pupils attain well, is much </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">smaller. The</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> weakest schools are spread </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">round the country, often in market or coastal towns, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">or in areas where the poorest children are spread thinly between schools i</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">n otherwise affluent areas.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.18pt; padding-left:2.82pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The performance of pupils who are eligible for free school meals varies greatly within and across local authorities. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">entire</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> regions, opportunities for pupils</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">from low income backgrounds look bleak. For</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">example, in the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">relatively affluent South East</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> in 2012</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-