/span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">leadership</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">working with pupils and parents to increase</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">engagement and raise expectations.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Gaps in achievement start early. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Inspection evidence </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">shows that the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">most successful childhood interventions encourage high levels of active parent</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">al</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> engagement in th</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">eir children’s learning</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">settings</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">that can do this </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">are more successful in closing the attainment gap for socially disadvantaged children. The</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">y </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">share their educational aims with parents and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">help</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> parents to support children at home with activities or mat</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">erials that complement what the setting is doing in its delivery of the EYFS curriculum.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">It is crucial that teachers in primary schools are</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">better equipped to assess and track the progress</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">of children from the start of their school career.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> This is particu</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">larly important for children from disadvantaged backgrounds. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Inspection evidence demonstrates that the best</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">primary schools</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">quickly assess each</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">child in terms of key skills such as reading,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">writing and grasp of numbers. They use this</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">baseline to inform tea</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ching and support for each</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">child. They link frequent assessments</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">of each child’s progress to their learning</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">and to the professional development and</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">performance management of their staff. The</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">schools that do this well achieve outstanding</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">results for all the</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ir children.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">In 2008, Ofsted highlighted common features</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">in schools that had </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">improved</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">the educational experiences and achievements</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">of white boy</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">s from low income backgrounds. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">These features</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">remain</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> relevant</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">support to develop boys’ organisation</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">skills and</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> instil the importance</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">of perseverance; any anti-school</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">subculture ‘left at the gates’</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">rigorous monitoring systems that track</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">individual pupils’ performance against</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">expectations; realistic but challenging</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">targets; tailored, flexible intervention</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> and frequent reviews</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">of performance against targets</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">a curriculum that is tightly structured</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">around individual needs and</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">linked to support programmes</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">that seek to raise aspirations</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">creative and flexible strategies to engage</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">parents and carers, make them fe</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">el valued,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">enable them to give greater support to</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">their sons’ education and help them make</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">informed decisions about the future</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">strong partnership with a wide</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">range of agencies to provide social,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">emotional, educational and practical</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">support for boys and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">their families</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">in order to raise their aspirations.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">In</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> 2013, Her Majesty’s Inspectors </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">visited 17 </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">schools </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">where the achievement of White British pupils from low income backgro</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">unds was strong or</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> had improved rapidly. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The schools were generally in areas of </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">high deprivation and had higher than average proportion of pupils who were eligible for free school meals and who were of White British background.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> A</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> report</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">No Child Left Unseen</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">will be published shortly. It </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">identifies approaches that other schools might</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> use to improve their provision and to raise the achievement of disadvantaged children.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> Some of these are summarised below:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The schools in the survey had </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">very </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">strong leaders who were determined to get the best out of all their pupils, whatever their backg</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">rounds.  They recognised that low achievement cannot be tackled in isolation and account has to be taken of a range of personal challenges that children from low income families often face. However, these headteachers did not accept that personal problems </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">inevitably led to underachievement. Instead, they were relentless in helping children to develop the resilience to deal with and overcome the difficulties that they faced and to keep striving for success.  </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The most successful schools ensured that children in need of additional help were identified as soon as possible, and that no time was wasted in providing them with appropriate support and intervention. The primary schools worked closely with children’s ce</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ntres and other providers to do this and also with secondary schools to ensure effective transition to the next stage of education. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The schools</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> adapted their practice in the light of the evidence and were not afraid to jettison any approaches that were n</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ot having the desired impact in raising </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">achievement</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> for disadvantaged pupils</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Fundamental to the approach adopted by these schools was the</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ir</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">pro-active </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">focus on supporting not only the children but also their families. Successful approaches included: </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">establishing a variety of informal as well as formal channels of communication with families; providing adult literacy and parenting courses; giving advice and providing resources to support learning at home.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">he schools in the survey ensured that childre</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">n had access to a rich and varied curriculum, both within and outside the classroom. The use of Pupil Premium funding and other concessionary systems ensured that children from low income families were included in all these activities.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">espite their succe</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ss, the schools visited had been given little opportunity to share their good practice. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">These </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">successful </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">schools wanted to share their experiences more widely.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">London Challenge and the city challenge programme were high </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">profile </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">and successful </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">area</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">based </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">itiatives that improved the quality of schools and raise</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> achievement. In London, all pupils, not just those from minority ethnic backgrounds benefited. The London and City Challenge programmes point to the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">potential impact</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> of </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">area</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">based</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> initiatives with t</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">he following characteristics:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:FoundryFormSans-Book; font-size:12pt">a high level of political will</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:FoundryFormSans-Book; font-size:12pt">and accountability</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">a clear focus on raising achievement for the most disadvantaged pupils</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">a shared purpose that involves the best local leaders and schools in directly supporting other schools i</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">n strengthening the leadership and teaching workforce</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">support and challenge through external, expert advisers who could broker bespoke solutions</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">sufficient flexibility to respond to the specific needs and context of the target area </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">sufficient executive</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> powers to take decisive action where improvement is too slow.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The potential for a wider range of educational approaches, for example vocational pathways, to improve outcomes for white working class pupils</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">In her review of Vocational Education, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Professor Wolf found that for some young people, following a vocational route at 14 resulted in them doing better in the core academic subjects as well. From September, 2013, general further education colleges judged to be good or outstanding for overall e</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ffectiveness at their last inspection have been able to enrol 14 to 16-year-olds on full-time provision. Ofsted will inspect this provision under the Common Inspection Framework for FE and Skills 2012. However, such provision would need to be promoted as a</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">n equal route to the academic route. Ofsted’s recent survey on career guidance found that vocational education and training, including apprenticeships, was still perceived as the subordinate route.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What role Government can play in delivering improved e</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ducational outcomes for white working class pupils </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">In the recent </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">report, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Unseen Children: access and achievement </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">– 20 years on</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> Ofsted made a number of key recommendations to government and policy makers</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">These recommendations focused on what could happ</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">en to</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> improve the quality of provision in the most disadvantaged areas and</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> accelerate the progress that has been made in improving the achievement of pupils</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> from low income backgrounds</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Those</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">most pertinent to this response</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> included:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Ofsted </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">be</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> tougher with</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">schools which are letting down their poor children. Schools previously judged</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">outstanding, which are not doing well by their poorest children, will be</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">reinspected</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">A call for </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">the development and roll-out of sub-regional</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">challenges aimed parti</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">cularly at raising the achievement of disadvantaged</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">children</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">, including those from White British backgrounds</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">A call for </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">a more strategic approach </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">to be</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">taken to the</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">appointment of National Leaders of Education and their matching with schools</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">in need of su</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">pport.</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Recommending that </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">government </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">do</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> more to ensure that</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">teachers on funded schemes </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">(such as Teach First) </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">are directed to underperforming schools in less</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">fashionable or more remote or challenging places. </span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Calling on the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">government to review assessment in</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> reception</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">and Key Stage 1, with a view to publishing progress measures from the start</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">of school to the end of Key Stage 1.</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Requiring all post-16 providers to </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">report</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">on the rate of progress and outcomes for all young people who had previously</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">been eligible</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> for free school meals.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt">Deprivation is based on the Income Deprivation Affecting Children Index (IDACI) 2010. The deprivation of a provider is </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt">based on the mean of the deprivation indices associated with the home post codes of the pupils attending the school rather than the location of the school itself. The schools are divided into five equal groups (quintiles) that are labelled from ‘most depri</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt">ved’ to ‘least deprived’.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> ‘</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt">Unseen children: access and achievement in education 20 years on</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt">http://www.ofsted.gov.uk/accessandachievement</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/review-of-vocational-education-the-wolf-report</span></p></body></html>